In [4]:
from pymc3 import Model, Uniform, Bernoulli

with Model() as coin_flip_model:
    # Prior
    p_heads = Uniform('p_heads', lower=0, upper=1) 
    # Likelihood
    obs = Bernoulli('obs', p=p_heads, observed=flips)

Bayesian Perceptron¶

In [15]:
from pymc3 import Normal
from pymc3.math import dot, sigmoid

n_dim = X.shape[1] # 2

with Model() as perceptron:
    # Define parameters, specify priors
    weights = Normal('w', mu=0, sd=.1, 
                     shape=n_dim) # [w1, w2]
    
    linear = dot(X, weights)
    class_prob = sigmoid(linear)
    
    # Binary classification -> Bernoulli likelihood
    Bernoulli('out', p=class_prob, observed=Y)

Bayesian Neural Network¶

Specify priors on weights¶

In [26]:
n_hidden = 5 # 2 hidden layers of 5 neurons each

with pm.Model() as neural_network:   
    # Weights from input to hidden layer
    weights_in_1 = Normal('w_in_1', 0, sd=1, 
                          shape=(n_dim, n_hidden), 
                          testval=init_1)
    
    # Weights from 1st to 2nd layer
    weights_1_2 = Normal('w_1_2', 0, sd=1, 
                         shape=(n_hidden, n_hidden), 
                         testval=init_2)
    
    # Weights from hidden layer to output
    weights_2_out = Normal('w_2_out', 0, sd=1, 
                           shape=(n_hidden,), 
                           testval=init_out)

Connect layers to likelihood¶

In [27]:
from pymc3.math import tanh

with neural_network:
    # input * weights1 => act_1
    act_1 = tanh(dot(X_shared, weights_in_1))
    # act_1 * weights2 => act2
    act_2 = tanh(dot(act_1, weights_1_2))
    # act2 * weights3 => output
    class_prob = sigmoid(dot(act_2, weights_2_out))
    
    # Likelihood
    Bernoulli('out', p=class_prob, observed=Y_shared)

Allowing weights to change over time¶

Before: $ w \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)$

Idea: $ w_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)$,

but weights would change erratically over time.

Gaussian Random Walk¶

Better idea: $ w_t \sim \mathcal{N}(w_{t-1}, \sigma^2)$

$\sigma$ works like a step-size that controls how much $w_t$ can change from its previous value.

In [38]:

Perceptron with Changing Weights¶

In [39]:
from pymc3 import HalfNormal, GaussianRandomWalk
import theano.tensor as tt

n_dim = X.shape[1] # 2

with pm.Model() as random_walk_perceptron:
    step_size = HalfNormal('step_size', sd=1.)
    
    weights = GaussianRandomWalk('w', sd=step_size,
                                 shape=(len(Y), n_dim)) # 1000 x 2
      
    class_prob = sigmoid(tt.batched_dot(X, weights))
    
    # Binary classification -> Bernoulli likelihood
    Bernoulli('out', p=class_prob, observed=Y)

Random-Walk Bayesian Neural Network¶

In [50]:
with pm.Model() as random_walk_neural_network:
    step_size = pm.HalfNormal('step_size', sd=np.ones(n_hidden[0]), 
                              shape=n_hidden[0])
                 
    # Weights from input to hidden layer
    weights_in_1 = pm.GaussianRandomWalk('w1', sd=step_size, 
                                         shape=(interval, X.shape[1], n_hidden[0]),
                                         testval=init_1)
    
    weights_in_1_rep = tt.repeat(weights_in_1, 
                                 ann_input.shape[0] // interval, axis=0)
    
    weights_1_2 = pm.Normal('w2', mu=0, sd=1., 
                            shape=(1, n_hidden[0], n_hidden[1]),
                            testval=init_2)
    
    weights_1_2_rep = tt.repeat(weights_1_2, 
                                ann_input.shape[0], axis=0)
    
    weights_2_out = pm.Normal('w3', mu=0, sd=1.,
                              shape=(1, n_hidden[1]),
                              testval=init_out)
    
    weights_2_out_rep = tt.repeat(weights_2_out, 
                                  ann_input.shape[0], axis=0)
In [51]:
with random_walk_neural_network:
    # Build neural-network using tanh activation function
    act_1 = tt.tanh(tt.batched_dot(ann_input, 
                         weights_in_1_rep))
    act_2 = tt.tanh(tt.batched_dot(act_1, 
                         weights_1_2_rep))
    act_out = tt.nnet.sigmoid(tt.batched_dot(act_2, 
                                             weights_2_out_rep))
        
    # Binary classification -> Bernoulli likelihood
    out = pm.Bernoulli('out', act_out, observed=ann_output)
